		<h4>Week 26</h4>	
			<p><b>Baby :</b> By 26 weeks the baby is around 850 to 950 grams. Your baby will soon be feeling a little cramped in your uterus-  but not to worry, there's still plenty of space in there to grow. It just means your tiny gymnast will have less room for those somersaults, cartwheels and other Olympic feats.</p>
			<p>look who's looking!!! It's your baby! Her eyes- which have been closed for the past few months so that the retina, the part of the eye that allows images to come into focus, could develop - are beginning to open at 26 weeks pregnant. That means your baby is able to see what's going on now, though unfortunately the view in your uterus isn't all that exciting.</p>
			<p>but do try this at home for kicks. Try flashlight at your stomach, your little peanut might kick and response as in- get that light out of my eyes!!! Right now the iris which is coloured part of the eye still doesn't have much pigmentation that will fill in over the next month or two so it's too early to start getting your little ones eye colour.</p>
			<p>And even the colour your baby is born with might not be permanent shade. You may be kept guessing until she's a year old, with the most dramatic changes occurring by about six months.</p>
			<p>Look what else is going on this week: Your baby's brain wave activity is gearing up at this stage in fetal development, which means your little one can not only hear noises but can now also respond to them. Not in so many words, of course, but with an increase in pulse rate and movement. Baby's external ear is now developed and it is placed at the right place now it's time for inner ear to develop baby can now recognise his mother's voice.</p>
			<p>baby's lungs are now little bit developed and they can give it a try. the nostrils are slightly open so baby can breathe in and exhale  amniotic fluid.</p>
			<p>baby skeleton is still of cartilage. only some part of it is ossified so baby is needing more calcium during this period! the development of reproductive system is in the process uterus, fallopian tubes and vagina in girls are formed in boys the testicles are now starting to descend from abdomen into scrotum.</p>

			<p><b>Mother :</b> You will be delivering the best baby after 3 months. For now the baby is developing, growing, kicking, hiccuping and just enjoying the protected environment in your womb. Beginning Somewhere around the middle to the end of your second trimester for enlarging uterus swelks enough to push your abdomen forward, making your navel pop out. even though you have a way to go before your baby is "well done". Your belly button should revert back to its regular position a few months after delivery - though it may have then stressed out "lived in" look.</p>
			<p>if a full night's rest has become elusive welcome to the sleepless world of pregnancy insomnia. between heartburn and leg cramps bathroom runs and that big beach ball with producing navel -  it it's no wonder your body is having trouble coming down and drifting off but there are a lot of tactis  to try that should help keep you in bed instead of pacing the floor, including daytime exercise, daily dose of fresh air and limiting fluids before you hit the bed.</p>
			<p>As the baby's nervous system becomes more developed, fetal movements will become much more coordinated and as she gets bigger and stronger, those moments will become much more powerful and occasionally even painful to you. if your baby lands a good one that time he left hook might hurt- a lot.!</p>
			<p>Psychologist recommend to interact with the baby as much as possible from now onwards as vaby's nervous system is developing and now the baby can recognise your voice. It has been proven that music has a calming effect on baby so you should try listening to music that is calmer in tone. Pregnancy is no reason to shut yourself in so go on doing the activities which makes you happy and joyful. Just take care that you don't end up in an accident.</p>
			<p>Pay attention to what you eat because now the baby is growing and it will consume all of your nutrients, so make sure that you have enough in your stock.</p>

			<p><b>Tips</b></p>
			<p><b>Practice good posture :</b> In between your bulging belly and your aching back, it isn't easy to stand up ... never mind stand up straight. But avoid the tendency to thirst your hips and stomach forward. Don't worry! everyone knows your pregnant by now and try not to throw your shoulders back when you are walking. Instead think straight line between your shoulders and your hips when you are up and about and to see what that feels like, back up against the wall while you're at it. Do some standing pelvic tilts. Sit smart by putting a pillow behind your lower back for support.</p>
			<p><b>Wash up :</b> Wash your hands first and foremost - and also everything that's even remotely a part of the food preparation process including the food itself. Be extra vigilant about this when handling raw meets, eggs, poultry or fish - wash your hands with warm soapy water before, during and after you touch this foods and be sure to clean the utensils, cutting board and towels you handled along the way. wash the lids of the cans before you open them so dirt and bacteria want contaminate the contents. Wash fruits and veggies thoroughly it before eating them even the ones you intend to peel.</p>
			<p><b>Track baby's movements :</b> Every baby responds differently to mom's exercise routine. Some may be lulled to sleep by the movement while others might seem to start a workout of their own.</p>

