			<h4>Week 27</h4>
			<p><b>Baby :</b> by 27 weeks the baby is quite active it starts clenching and unclenching the fists, the baby starts feeling its own body parts, touches  his face and ears, blinks the eyes, starts sucking.</p>
			<p>Your baby may recognise both your and your partner's voice by now. His auditory development, or hearing is progressing as the network of nerves to the ears matures - though the sounds he hears are muffled thanks to the creamy coating of vernix covering them so this might be a good time to read and events into a baby or rather your tummy and a good chance to start memorizing those nursery rhymes and Lullabies you will need to be repeating pretty soon.</p>
			<p>All the internal organs are now maturing to operate functionally though they are still considered little bit immature if the baby is born at this time. The visual system of the baby also started developing and it starts recognising the light and shadow and reacts to the lights by turning towards that side. The eyes start to blink which were closed for so many months.</p>
			<p>Thyroid hormone are produced aggressively during this period of time as it is necessary for babies development of respiratory digestive cardiovascular as well as mental functions. Mom may feel better now because now the babies glands have started producing enzymes and hormones so that the endocrine system of mother does not have to bear the load of two.</p>
			<p>The babies respiratory system has started developing now but the alveoli are still full of amniotic fluid. The baby is now practising inhalation and exhalation and the lungs have started producing surfactant but it is still considered little immature to do the function on its own.</p>
			<p>there is a lot of room for baby to do somersault in the amniotic fluid.</p>

			<p><b>Mother :</b> The start of the third trimester may herald with repeated visits to your bathroom because of either incontinence of urine or inability to completely empty your bladder.</p>
			<p>This is because of the growing uterus which presses on your bladder so that it is stimulated and you feel frequent urge to visit the bathroom or it may cause pressure over your ureter which might cause backflow of urine and result into hydronephrosis, which may cause mild pain in your flank region . Even urine leak is also a major problem as you might feel very ashamed and uncomfortable when you might end up leaking urine while coughing, sneezing or laughing. Sometimes you may get confused whether it's a urine leak or the water bag around your baby is leaking so you might need to visit Hospital to get it checked. better to get it checked then to be confused.</p>
			<p>You may have noticed that your baby's schedule does not necessarily match yours. By the time you are going to fall asleep the baby will start kicking around because your movement while you are awake lulls the baby and makes it fall asleep but while you are calm the baby wakens  up. Try calming your baby by patting on your belly or listening to  calm music.</p>
			<p>Beginning somewhere around this stage of pregnancy nearly three in four pregnant women start to experience mild swelling of the extremities particularly the feet, ankles and hand, it occurs when fluid buildup in your body tissue. Thanks to increased blood flow and uterine pressure on the inferior vena cava the large vein on the right side of your body that returns blood from lower limbs to the heart.</p>

			<p><b>Tips</b></p>
			<p><b>Fight puffiness :</b> The two main culprits for under eye bags are water retention, see it's not just in your ankles and- fatigue, so try to get as much rest as possible and drink plenty of water to flush your system. The more you drink the less you retain. still puffier then you would like? here are some quick fixes - because bags are more prominent in the morning place something cool over your eyes, when you first wake up try the always favourite cucumber slices , cold tea bags , chilled spoons or a bag of frozen blueberries followed by a healthy helpings of concealer and eye-opening mascara.</p>
			<p><b>Monitor your heart rate :</b> Now that you are pumping for two, it is more important than ever to keep an eye on your heart rate when you are exercising. the best way to check how much you are exerting yourself is to use the exercise talk test - no need to take your pulse ! if you can't exercise and talk simultaneously your heart rate is probably too high.</p>
			<p><b>Prepare a food journal :</b> If it restless leg syndrome is driving you crazy try keeping a food journal and note what you eat before you experience of restless leg syndrome. Some woman find that certain food such as carbs eaten  late in the day can trigger restless leg. A journal may help you figure out what food makes your symptoms improve or worsen.</p>
			<p><b>Fight bloat :</b> We know you are gassy! it's normal! to help cover the problem you may start to swap flatulence causing foods like broccoli or less gassy- spinach and carrots. Also make sure to drink plenty of water and drop for smaller meals- the more food you pump into your stomach at a sitting, the more gas you will be pumping out.</p>
			<p><b>Soothe the heat rash :</b>Caused by the combination of an already overheated pregnant body, dampness from excessive perspiration and the friction of skin rubbing against itself or against clothing, as it tends to do when there are more skin. Heat rash shows up as prickly, pimply,  itchy, red patches on your skin. It is most common in the crease between and beneath the breasts, in the crease when the bulge of lower abdomen rubs against the top of a pubic area and on the inner thighs. A cool damp compress cn take some of the heat out of your rash. A dab of calamine lotion can also be temporarily soothing and is safe to use. if any rash or irritation lasts longer than a couple of days ask a practitioner about next steps.</p>

