			<h4>Week 29</h4>
			<p><b>Baby :</b> Over the course of time the baby who is weighing  right now around a kilogram will keep  on gaining weight almost double or triple of present. All the organ system of the body are ready to function, the baby can now regulate its own heat mechanism. The digestive tract is still a little immature but will soon mature in the coming third trimester.</p>
			<p>Though he is getting pretty close to his birth length he still has to grow a bit.  As more fat is deposited under the skin surface his wrinkled skin is now smoothing out. This fat as it's called is different from the earlier brown fat for developing foetus accumulated. Brown fat is necessary for body temperature regulation while white fat the same kind you have actually serves as an energy source.</p>
			<p>Since space in your baby's living quarters is now at a premium, you will be feeling jabs and pokes from elbows and knees, mostly. And they will be more vigorous and less erratic than before because your baby is stronger and excitedly responding to all sorts of stimuli- movements, sounds, light  and that candy bar you eat half an hour ago. That means now's a good time to start doing a kick count once or twice a day depending on what your doctor recommends plus it's a good excuse for rest.</p>
			<p>The baby's body start to shed Lenugo and vernix, and in most cases, by the time baby is born, it remains in creases.</p>
			<p>The reproductive system is nearly complete. in the boys the testis starts to descent, but they won't complete the descent out of abdomen until after the birth.</p>
			<p>The circulatory system has developed and all the elements to carry oxygen remove carbon dioxide are formed but yet the blood between arteries and veins mix a little bit.</p>
			<p>Another reason of weight gain is increasing bone mass, the bone now becomes harder. the baby needs to 250 milligram of calcium  everyday.</p>
			<p>the kidney keeps on developing now. the nasal passage is clear of mucus.  The fluid now enters baby's body via  nasal passage and mouth.</p>

			<p><b>Mother :</b> By week 29 the body starts preparing for the upcoming labour. The breast starts swelling up and the nipples main start  secreting the Colostrum. doctors specifically won not to squeeze the nipples because it may initiate the preterm labor. The most you can do is keep your breast clean and wear nursing pads to wick away the milk.</p>
			<p>By week 29 of pregnancy, your tummy  is probably large enough that you can't see your legs when you are standing anymore. And that could be a good thing if you like the roughly 20% of expected moms who develop varicose veins.</p>
			<p>This swollen blood vessels can either develop or worsen when you're expecting, though they are really cause for concern. they pop up because your blood volume increases during pregnancy, your growing uterus is putting pressure on pelvic veins and hormones are making your veins relax.</p>
			<p>Varicose veins are painful for some and not painful for others. Like stretch marks they can be passed on from generation to generation.</p>
			<p>Not only uterus but the baby inside is also growing, the baby is now rounded and stores the fat it needs. you should start counting the fetal kick by 29 weeks. Now the baby can't do flips quite easily as it used to do. Movements are the best indicator of babies well being. it's typically a 10 count in 12 hours. </p>
			<p>Do not panic if for some hours you don't feel the baby's movement that's because the baby is also sleeping.</p>

			<p><b>Tips</b></p>
			<p><b>Breast pads! :</b> Stock some breast pads now because your breast might start leaking a thin yellowish fluid called colostrum.</p>
			<p><b>Restless legs syndrome :</b> Between heartburns, leg cramps that urgent need to use the loo every two hours and an insistent case of pregnancy insomnia, you are already having a tough time getting quality shut eye. noone is quite sure why but another pregnancy symptom is keeping you up all night and that is restless leg syndrome. Make sure you get enough iron in your diet and enough movement during the day.</p>
			<p><b>UTI :</b> You are more susceptible to urinary tract infections this trimester other symptoms include lower abdominal pain and cloudy dark, bloody or foul smelling urine.</p>
			<p><b>Sensitive skin :</b> Your rising hormones can make you more sensitive to contact with substances that might not normally affect you, such as sunlight, heat detergents, chlorine even certain foods and if you have got eczema you can expect some major flare ups.</p>
		
